  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Dispatch Congratulating the Wang Heir on His Investiture
  author: Kim Geukgi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    We, your servants, humbly submit:

    We have learned that on the fifteenth of this month, the Crown Prince received his seal of office, and on the twenty-sixth, he received congratulations from all within and without the realm. The Northern Star has descended with golden decrees, showering grace and honor upon us. The Eastern Palace opens its jade-wrought gates, and radiant titles and mandate are bestowed. This brings blessing to all living things and joy to the ten thousand nations. We, your servants, are moved with genuine delight and gratitude, and we bow our heads in reverence.

    We humbly reflect: The Crown Prince's filial piety surpasses the three dynasties, and his talents exceed the five excellences. His writings flow like clouds and spring forth like fountains, outshining the literary brilliance of Cao Cao's heir. His learning advances day by day and month by month, illuminating heights beyond even the wisdom of King Cheng of Zhou. Long has he possessed the virtue to inherit his heritage, and now justly does he ascend to the honored station of regent of the realm.

    In this auspicious moment, he receives the precious seal. The light of the first star now shines brighter still, adding radiance to sovereign brilliance. Even as small waves break upon the shore, they aid the great waters. Joy spreads equally to distant and near, and fortune transcends all ages.

    Though we, your servants, are burdened with imperial commission and distant military duties, we rejoice as sparrows and swallows greeting one another at the completion of a great hall. Yet like wild geese soaring high above, we lament that distance prevents us from witnessing this glory in person.

    Unable to contain our reverent admiration and overwhelming awe, we now dispatch the official [name] to present this dispatch and offer our humble congratulations.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Cao Cao's heir refers to Cao Pi, known for his literary accomplishments in the Wei Dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: King Cheng of Zhou was revered as an exemplary ruler whose wisdom and learning set the standard for sage-kings.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of sparrows and wild geese reflects the speaker's position—joy at the heir's elevation tempered by the distance and duties that prevent their full participation in the celebration.
